/ul><div class=\"toggle-trigger\"><p class=\"trigger-line lazyload\"><span class=\"trigger-arrow\"></span></p></div>\n	      \n  </div>\n  \n\n  <p class=\"cite-feedback\">These example sentences are selected automatically from various online news sources to reflect current usage of the word \'site.\' Views expressed in the examples do not represent the opinion of Merriam-Webster or its editors. <a href=\"/contact-us?ref=freshexamples&amp;hw=site&amp;fl=noun&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.merriam-webster.com%2Fdictionary%2Fsite\">Send us feedback</a>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>                                               \n                                                                                                                                        <div class=\"little-gems-box card-box simple-def-box secondary-card verb-def-box little-gems-module-anchor\">\n  <div class=\"inner-box-wrapper\">\n    <h2>\n      <i>cite</i>, <i>sight</i>, and <i>site</i>\n    </h2>\n    <div class=\"card-primary-content def-text\">\n        <p>The three <a href=\"/dictionary/homophone\">homophones</a> <a href=\"/dictionary/cite\"><em>cite</em></a>, <a href=\"/dictionary/sight\"><em>sight</em></a>, and <a href=\"/dictionary/site\"><em>site</em></a> are occasionally confused by some people when used as nouns (<em>sight</em> and <em>site</em>) or as verbs (all three words). They needn&rsquo;t cause trouble:  with a little thought, most people who struggle with them can settle upon the correct choice.</p>\n\n<p><em>Cite</em> is most often encountered in the sense of &ldquo;to name in a <a href=\"/dictionary/citation\">citation</a>&rdquo;; it may also mean &ldquo;to mention as an example&rdquo; or &ldquo;to order to appear in a court of law.&ldquo;</p>\n\n<p>Most of the senses of <em>sight</em> are concerned with the act or action of <em>seeing</em>. A wonderful spectacle might be described as a <em>sight</em>, as might the general capacity to see anything (&ldquo;my sight is not as good as it once was&rdquo;). </p>\n\n<p><em>Site</em> is most often concerned with location; it is related to the verb <em>situate</em> \"to locate\" and <em>situation</em> \"a position.\" A building <em>site</em> is the place where the building is, or will be, located.  In contemporary English, <em>site</em> has increasingly been used as a shortened form of <em>website</em>, for the location of a specific page on the Internet.</p>\n\n<p>If you connect <em>citation</em> with <em>cite</em>, <em>eyesight</em> with <em>sight</em>, and <em>situate</em> with <em>site</em>, you are unlikely to make an error.  </p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"card-box small-box origin-box  \">\n  <div class=\"inner-box-wrapper\">\n    <h2 class=\"card-box-title\">\n      Origin and Etymology of <i>site</i>\n    </h2>\n  \n    <div class=\"card-primary-content\">\n      <p>\n        </p><div class=\"et\"><!--\n  --><!--\n    --><!--\n      -->Middle English, place, position, from Anglo-French or Latin; Anglo-French <em class=\"mw_t_it\">sit, site</em>, from Latin <em class=\"mw_t_it\">situs</em>, from <em class=\"mw_t_it\">sinere</em> to leave, allow<!--\n    --><!--\n  --><!--\n--></div>      \n              <div id=\"origin-explorer\">\n          <div class=\"explorer-wrapper invisible\">\n            <div class=\"blue-box\"><span class=\"new-text\">NEW! Time Traveler</span></div>            <p class=\"no-padding\">First Known Use: 14th century</p>\n            <p class=\"ety-sl\" data-entry-id=\"1\">in the meaning defined at <a href=\"#\">sense 1a</a></p>\n            <a href=\"/time-traveler/14th-century?src=defrecirc-timetraveler-etycard\">See Words from the same year<span class=\"fa fa-chevron-right\"></span></a>          </div>\n        </div>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card-box small-box thesaurus-synonyms-box end\">\n  <div class=\"inner-box-wrapper\">\n    <h2 class=\"card-box-title\"><i>site</i> Synonyms</h2>\n    <div class=\"card-primary-content\